### 11. `truncate` function performs double work when string fits

- **Severity**: Low
- **File**: `/Users/heejoon.kang/dev/git/fenv-org/mementor/crates/mementor-lib/src/transcript/types.rs` (lines 76-94)
- **Issue**: When `s.len() > max_graphemes` but the grapheme count still fits (i.e., `end == s.len()` after the loop), the function calls `s.to_string()` -- creating an allocation identical to the early return at line 81. This second `s.to_string()` path (line 90) is correct but the logic flow is slightly confusing. Restructuring to a single exit point or using an early return when `end == s.len()` would be clearer, though the current code works correctly.
- **Before**:
```rust
fn truncate(s: &str, max_graphemes: usize) -> String {
    if s.len() <= max_graphemes {
        return s.to_string();
    }
    let mut end = s.len();
    for (count, (idx, _)) in s.grapheme_indices(true).enumerate() {
        if count == max_graphemes {
            end = idx;
            break;
        }
    }
    if end == s.len() {
        s.to_string()
    } else {
        format!("{}...", &s[..end])
    }
}
```
- **After**:
```rust
fn truncate(s: &str, max_graphemes: usize) -> String {
    // Fast path: when byte length fits, grapheme count must also fit.
    if s.len() <= max_graphemes {
        return s.to_string();
    }
    // Find the byte index of the max_graphemes-th grapheme cluster.
    let boundary = s
        .grapheme_indices(true)
        .nth(max_graphemes)
        .map(|(idx, _)| idx);
    match boundary {
        Some(idx) => format!("{}...", &s[..idx]),
        None => s.to_string(), // Fewer graphemes than max -- no truncation needed.
    }
}
```

